\begin_layout Title
An invitation to projection methods 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Heinz H.
 Bauschke
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Feasibility problems, i.e., finding a solution satisfying certain constraints,
 are common in mathematics and the natural sciences.
 If the constraints have simple projectors (nearest point mappings), then
 one approach is to use these projectors in some algorithmic fashion to
 approximate a solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In this talk, I will survey three methods (alternating projections, Dykstra,
 and Douglas-Rachford), and comment on recent advances and remaining challenges.
\end_layout

